'''GM-AvtoVAZ''' is a joint venture in Russia between [[General Motors]] and [[AvtoVAZ]] set up in 2001 and began producing the [[Chevrolet Niva]], based on the Lada Niva, at its factory in [[Tolyatti]] from 2002. Though both companies have an equal share of ownership, the venture is managed exclusively by General Motors.<ref>{{cite news|title=«Когда-то Lada по сравнению с Dacia считалась люксовым брендом»|url=https://www.vedomosti.ru/auto/characters/2016/06/14/645207-kompaniyu-pribilnosti|accessdate=7 July 2017|publisher=Vedomosti|date=13 June 2016|quote=– В этом СП «АвтоВАЗа» и GM по 50%, но фактически управляет им GM? – Да.Мы являемся для них важным поставщиком и обсуждаем условия по новой платформе.}}</ref>

==History==
[[File:Chevrolet Niva Concept.JPG|thumb|left|[[Chevrolet Niva]]]]
In 2004 the joint venture briefly produced the [[Chevrolet Viva]], based on the 1998 [[Opel Astra]] saloon, but after low sales of only 5,000 the model was dropped.<ref name=Bloomberg>{{cite web|title=GM: Learning the Ropes In Russia|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2007-02-08/gm-learning-the-ropes-in-russiabusinessweek-business-news-stock-market-and-financial-advice|work=Bloomberg Business Week|accessdate=18 December 2012|date=8 February 2007}}</ref>

The joint venture reached difficulties and production stoppages for a fortnight in February 2006 when AvtoVAZ was taken over by [[Rosoboronexport]], the Russian state-owned arms-export agency, and a disagreement between the new owners and GM lead to stoppages of the supply of engines and other components.<ref name=Bloomberg/>

The joint venture announced plans in September 2012 to expand by 2015, with an additional 1400 staff and increasing its annual production capacity from 100,000 to 120,000 vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|title=GM-AvtoVaz To Expand Capacity By 20% By 2015|url=https://www.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20120921-702821.html|work=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=18 December 2012|date=21 September 2012}}</ref>

==Ownership==
[[File:Russia Re-Industrializes as Energy Boom Fades.theora.ogv|thumbnail|[[Voice of America]] report, showing operations inside the plant and an interview with a representative from GM Russia.]]
The joint venture was created with investment from GM ($99.1m, 41.61%), AvtoVAZ ($99.1m, 41.61%) and the [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]] ($40m, 16,78%, plus a loan facility for $100 million). In September 2012 GM and Avtovaz purchased EBRD's share, turning the joint venture into a 50/50 relationship.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Company|url=http://gm-avtovaz.ru/en/company/chevrolet_niva/|website=GM Avtovaz|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref>

==Products==
As of December 2014, the joint venture has produced 571,852 vehicles since production at Tolyatti commenced in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Production and Sales Results|url=http://gm-avtovaz.ru/en/company/news/2014_production_and_sales_results/|website=GM AutoVAZ|accessdate=22 January 2015|date=31 December 2014}}</ref>

*[[Chevrolet Niva]] (1998-present)
*[[Chevrolet Viva]] (2004-2005)

