[[File:Hacienda Pleasanton traffic lights.jpg|thumb|right|Distinctive motif for traffic lights in Hacienda Business Park]] '''Hacienda Business Park''' is a 900 acre (364 hectare) mixed-use job center and housing development in [[Pleasanton, California]].<ref name="mix">{{cite web |url = http://www.ftscities.com/Pleasanton_Hacienda_Business_Park |title = Hacienda Business Park Transit-Oriented Specific Plan |accessdate = 2011-01-08 |publisher = Freedman Tung + Sasaki Urban Design }}</ref><ref name="laws">{{cite news | author = Jeb Bing | title = Council, affordable housing coalitions, expected to settle legal battle for $1.9 million tonight | url = http://www.pleasantonweekly.com/news/show_story.php?id=4642 | work = [[Pleasanton Weekly]] | date = 2010-07-20 | accessdate = 2011-01-08 }}</ref>
==History== Approved in 1982 and ratified by Pleasanton voters in 1983,<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.hacienda.org/presentations/home.html |title = Presentations / View Presentations / History |accessdate = 2011-01-08 |publisher = Hacienda Business Park Owners Association |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110726135439/http://www.hacienda.org/presentations/home.html |archivedate = 2011-07-26 |df = }}</ref> the business park covers approximately 20 square blocks and features many multi-story office buildings and headquarters for mid-sized companies. It was envisioned by local and [[Alameda County, California|county]] planners as a location for office space that would be less expensive than that of [[Silicon Valley]] or [[San Francisco]], close to housing in Pleasanton and nearby [[Dublin, California|Dublin]] as well as the homes of existing employees in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]]. In 2010, the city settled a lawsuit to allow for more affordable housing development in the area.<ref name="laws"/>
==Location== It is located adjacent to the [[Dublin/Pleasanton BART station]].<ref name="mix"/> [[Tri-Delta Transit]]'s DX or "Delta Express" line also connects to this station, providing "luxury" commuter express bus service from the East County region of [[Contra Costa County]] including the cities of [[Antioch, California|Antioch]], [[Oakley, California|Oakley]], [[Brentwood, California|Brentwood]], and [[Discovery Bay, California|Discovery Bay]], as well as the town of [[Mountain House, San Joaquin County, California|Mountain House]] in [[San Joaquin County]] in the [[California Central Valley|Central Valley]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.trideltatransit.com/promo_dxpress_free_week.aspx |title = Delta Express |accessdate = 2011-01-08 |publisher = [[Tri Delta Transit]] |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100820154409/http://www.trideltatransit.com/promo_dxpress_free_week.aspx |archivedate = 2010-08-20 |df = }}</ref> [[San Joaquin Regional Transit District|San Joaquin Regional Transit District (SMART)]] provides commuter subscription service from the central valley on several lines in addition to local service provided by [[WHEELS (California)|WHEELS]] and the [[County Connection]].
